THE BEHAVIORAL HEALTH OF THE CREW DURING A MISSION TO MARS MISSION COULD BE CHALLENGED DUE TO THE CONDITIONS REQUIRED BY THE FLIGHT. HOWEVER THERE IS NO STANDARDIZED METHOD TO DETECT AND QUANTIFY THE MAGNITUDE OF THE RISK OR ITS LIKELIHOOD. THE OVERARCHING GOAL OF THIS PROJECT IS TO BUILD ON A SUCCESSFUL RECORD OF UNOBTRUSIVE, SOFTWARE-BASED MEASUREMENT OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH INDICATORS EG MOOD, COGNITIVE FUNCTION, PHYSICAL AND MENTAL FATIGUE, SLEEP QUALITY TO DEVELOP AN INTEGRATED STANDARDIZED SUITE OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH MEASUREMENT TOOLS THAT WOULD BE QUITE FEASIBLE TO IMPLEMENT WITHIN THE CONSTRAINTS OF SPACEFLIGHT RESEARCH, GROUND-BASED ANALOGS BOTH SHORT AND LONG DURATION, AND PROLONGED MISSIONS IN ISOLATED, CONFINED, EXTREME ENVIRONMENTS LASTING UP TO 12 MONTHS OR LONGER. ACHIEVEMENT OF THIS GOAL WOULD PERMIT A MORE RAPID AND RELIABLE ASSESSMENT AND QUANTIFICATION OF THE RISK OF ADVERSE BEHAVIORAL CONDITIONS PSYCHIATRIC OUTCOMES FOR EXPLORATION CLASS MISSIONS. THE SUITE OF BEHAVIORAL MEDICINE MEASURES WE ARE DEVELOPING WILL BE INTEGRATED ON APPLE IPAD PLATFORM FOR THEIR STANDARDIZED USE IN GROUND ANALOGS RELEVANT TO THE SPACEFLIGHT CONTEXT IE STANDARDIZED BEHAVIORAL MEASURES TOOL OR SBMT. IT WILL INCLUDE THE COGNITION BATTERY, VISUAL ANALOG SCALES VAS OF PERCEIVED MENTAL AND PHYSICAL EXHAUSTION, FATIGUE, STRESS, WORKLOAD, CONFLICT AND SLEEP QUALITY, ACTIGRAPHY FOR MONITORING SLEEP WAKE ACTIVITY, AN AUDIO JOURNAL, THE SPACE DOCK TASK AS AN OPERATIONAL PERFORMANCE MEASURE, AND ADDITIONAL NON-INVASIVE MEASURES RELEVANT TO BEHAVIORAL MEDICINE INFORMED BY A COMPREHENSIVE LITERATURE REVIEW. THE SBMT WILL BE EVALUATED FOR INCLUSION OF THE TASK OF TAKING THE INFORMATION ON MEASUREMENT FEASIBILITY, FLEXIBILITY AND ACCEPTABILITY DURING POST MISSION ASSESSMENTS IN THE PARTICIPANTS STUDIED IN HERA, HI SEAS AND ON ISS. IT WILL BE IMPROVED AS NEEDED, AND AN OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES DOCUMENT WILL BE DEVELOPED TO MAKE IT USE CONVENIENT AND UNOBTRUSIVE FOR DETECTING THE INCIDENT RATE OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH RISKS IN SPACE AND ON EARTH.

doc.ContractDescription: WITHIN THE NEXT 5-25 YEARS, ASTRONOMERS HOPE TO OBTAIN SPECTRA OF ROCKY PLANETS WITHIN THE HABITABLE ZONES OF NEARBY STARS. THE SHORTER TIME FRAME APPLIES IF TESS SUCCEEDS IN FINDING A NEARBY M STAR WITH A TRANSITING, POTENTIALLY HABITABLE PLANET AND IF JWST IS THEN ABLE TO TAKE TRANSIT SPECTRA OF ITS ATMOSPHERE. THE LONGER TIME FRAME APPLIES IF NONE OF THE SMALL EXO-C S OR MEDIUM-SIZED WFIRST AFTA DIRECT IMAGING MISSIONS CURRENTLY BEING STUDIED SUCCEEDS IN FINDING AND CHARACTERIZING AN EARTH-LIKE PLANET AND IF PLANNING FOR LARGER SPACE TELESCOPES TPF, NWO, LUVOIR, OR ATLAST IS POSTPONED UNTIL 2030 OR LATER. ONCE SPECTROSCOPIC DATA FROM POTENTIALLY HABITABLE PLANETS BECOME AVAILABLE, QUESTIONS WILL IMMEDIATELY ARISE AS TO WHETHER THESE PLANETS ARE A HABITABLE, OR B INHABITED. LOOKING FOR EVIDENCE OF LIFE, EG, THE PRESENCE OF O2 OR ITS PHOTOCHEMICAL BYPRODUCT, O3, IS NOT TREMENDOUSLY MORE DIFFICULT THAN LOOKING FOR H2O, AS O2 SHOWS MEASUREABLE ABSORPTION AT 0.76 UM, AND O3 HAS STRONG BANDS IN BOTH THE NEAR-UV AND THERMAL-IR. FOLLOWING LOVELOCK NATURE, 1964, MOST RESEARCHERS AGREE THAT THE SIMULTANEOUS PRESENCE OF O2 OR O3 AND A REDUCED GAS, SUCH AS CH4 OR N2O, WOULD BE STRONG EVIDENCE FOR LIFE. BUT THAT COMBINATION MAY BE DIFFICULT TO OBSERVE WITH A FIRST GENERATION DIRECT-IMAGING TELESCOPE BECAUSE THE LATTER TWO GASES ARE NOT SUFFICIENTLY ABUNDANT TO BE DETECTABLE AT LOW SPECTRAL RESOLUTION, AT LEAST ON MODERN EARTH. HENCE, THE QUESTION ARISES: IS O2 OR O3, BY ITSELF, A RELIABLE BIOINDICATOR, OR ARE THERE FALSE POSITIVES FOR LIFE IN WHICH THESE GASES ARE PRODUCED ABIOTICALLY? THE LITERATURE ON THIS TOPIC ACTUALLY DATES BACK MORE THAN 50 YEARS BERKNER AND MARSHALL, 1964, 1965, 1966, 1967. THESE RESEARCHERS WERE NOT INTERESTED IN EXOPLANETS; RATHER, THEY WANTED TO KNOW HOW MUCH O2 WAS PRESENT IN EARTH S ATMOSPHERE PRIOR TO THE ORIGIN OF OXYGENIC PHOTOSYNTHESIS. THEIR IDEAS WERE NOT QUITE RIGHT, BECAUSE THEY DID NOT FULLY UNDERSTAND HOW HYDROGEN ESCAPES FROM EARTHS ATMOSPHERE; HOWEVER, THEY INITIATED SEVERAL DECADES OF STUDY BY OTHER RESEARCHERS SEEKING TO ANSWER THIS SAME QUESTION. MOST RECENTLY, THREE DIFFERENT GROUPS HAVE STUDIED ASPECTS OF THIS PROBLEM USING DETAILED, 1D PHOTOCHEMICAL MODELS HU ET AL., APJ, 2012 TIAN ET AL., EPSL, 2014; DOMAGAL-GOLDMAN ET AL., APJ, 2014. THEIR RESULTS, HOWEVER, ARE NOT ALWAYS IN GOOD AGREEMENT. FOR EXAMPLE, FOR A PLANET WITH A 95 PERCENT N2, 5 PERCENT CO2 ATMOSPHERE ORBITING AN M STAR, TIAN ET AL. PREDICT AN OBSERVABLE O2 COLUMN DEPTH OF 8 10 22 CM -2, WHEREAS DOMAGAL-GOLDMAN ET AL. PREDICT AN UNOBSERVABLE O2 COLUMN DEPTH OF 8 10 18 CM -2. THIS DISCREPANCY IS CURIOUS, ESPECIALLY AS THESE TWO PHOTOCHEMICAL MODELS SHARE A COMMON HERITAGE FROM THE KASTING RESEARCH GROUP. THE HU ET AL. MODEL, BY CONTRAST, WAS DEVELOPED INDEPENDENTLY, AND SO PROVIDES A USEFUL CHECK ON THESE OTHER MODELS. WE PROPOSE TO PERFORM A DETAILED INTERCOMPARISON BETWEEN THE MODELS OF HU ET AL., DOMAGAL-GOLDMAN ET AL., AND OUR OWN KASTING GROUP PARENT MODEL, LOOKING AT PLANETS WITH DIFFERENT ATMOSPHERIC COMPOSITIONS ORBITING DIFFERENT TYPES OF STARS. WE SUSPECT THAT MANY OF THE DIFFERENCES BETWEEN MODELS HAVE TO DO WITH HOW THE ATMOSPHERIC REDOX BUDGET IS BALANCED AND WHAT TYPES OF LOWER BOUNDARY CONDITIONS ARE IMPOSED FOR GASES SUCH AS CO AND O2. THE LOWER BOUNDARY CONDITIONS SHOULD DEPEND ON HOW FAST DISSOLVED GASES WITHIN THE OCEANS REACT WITH EACH OTHER AND WITH OTHER SPECIES E.G., FE THAT MAY BE PRESENT. WE WILL ESTIMATE APPROXIMATE RATES FOR SUCH REACTIONS USING AB INITIO QUANTUM MECHANICAL MODELING. A MORE AMBITIOUS PROJECT, INVOLVING WET CHEMISTRY EXPERIMENTS TO EVALUATE THESE RATES, IS PLANNED IN THE MORE DISTANT FUTURE. THIS WORK IS RELEVANT TO HABITABLE WORLDS BECAUSE IT BEARS ON THE QUESTION OF HOW POTENTIALLY HABITABLE, BUT LIFELESS, WORLDS COULD APPEAR TO BE INHABITED. THUS, IT WILL HELP DEVELOP OUR ABILITY TO PLACE FUTURE REMOTE BIOSIGNATURES IN THEIR PROPER PLANETARY CONTEXT.
